note.body:
You can use this as a starting point.

```bash
python3 -m venv .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
pip install meson ninja packaging
git clone --depth 1 https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gtk
meson setup -Dx11-backend=false -Dintrospection=disabled -Dmedia-gstreamer=disabled --prefix=$(pwd)/install _build gtk
meson compile -C _build
meson install -C _build

curl -L -o lcms2-2.16.tar.gz https://sourceforge.net/projects/lcms/files/lcms/2.16/lcms2-2.16.tar.gz/download
tar xzf lcms2-2.16.tar.gz
cd lcms2-2.16; ./configure --prefix $(pwd)/install; make; make install; cd ..
```

> I am _the person_ to talk

heh, nice

Mostly thinking about development before digging into CI. How do I install meson to begin with?

I am _the person_ to talk to. Are you asking about setting yourself up or are you thinking about macOS CI in this project?

Generally speaking, it depends on how big the project/its list of dependencies is. For example, GTK can be built just with meson and ninja, it has subprojects to take care of all of its dependencies on its own, which is pretty neat (granted, you have to disable features like gstreamer and introspection for that). In more complex situations, you keep adding additional "clone; configure; make install" steps to that until it makes sense to pull out "the big guns" and use JHBuild.

note.body: Hi, I was looking whether it was possible to port gnome-contacts to libglycin and got stuck on this particular issue (since we only get a `GLoadableIcon` from the lower stack, which only provides a `GInputStream` ouptut). Would another possibility be to support `GInputStream` rather than (or together with) GBytes as an API? It's pretty trivial to transform both a `GBytes` or a `GFile` to an input stream, so that might be a more featureful API to implement?

note.body: The README proposes `image/qoi` https://github.com/phoboslab/qoi?tab=readme-ov-file#mime-type-file-extension

image-rs also uses `x-qoi`

- https://github.com/image-rs/image/blob/2125965fdc23ea0544fd585f6e934cc7762c1f51/src/image.rs#L189
- https://github.com/image-rs/image/blob/2125965fdc23ea0544fd585f6e934cc7762c1f51/src/image.rs#L235

Maybe XDG should consider changing the default to x-qoi \*sigh\*
Ah, I assumed that you would get the same error message. But I tested it and you don't. So yeah, this has to be adjusted in the loader.
? I posted above that I already tried changing that file.
See https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glycin#image-loader-configuration
This has nothing to do at all with rebuilding Loupe. You need to change the config file on your system. That should be `/usr/share/glycin-loaders/1+/conf.d/glycin-image-rs.conf` on your system.

I did and even went into the source for glycin and changed all references to x-qoi to qoi and rebuilt loupe with gnome-builder and it showed the config in the output as x-qoi still. I may just need to restart but it seemed like the build from gnome-builder was using a built-in configuration instead of the XDG_DATA_DIRS config. This was the first time I used gnome-builder so I may have missed something. I'm just doing a full restart now to test.
PS: You need to restart Loupe for your config change to take effect.

Thanks for reporting the issue.

Looks like QOI was only added back on April 4, 2023, to the XDG mime types. Therefore, the previous entry in glycin's default config was just a guess. I failed to catch that in #20.

That they went with `qoi` instead of `x-qoi` is a bit curious, since `x-qoi` has been [in use before](https://github.com/phoboslab/qoi/issues/167). I guess it would be best to keep `x-qoi` as well.

If I file a bug about glycin, how would I find the version number of glycin I am using?

Would you get confused as to what glycin 1.0.1 is referring to or am I the only one confused?

Hi,

there is a global version number for this repository as was suggest in the RT channel, which cannot be in sync with the single components. There are

- glycin (crate)
- glycin-utils (crate)
- libglycin (C library)
- libglycin-gtk4 (C library)
- loaders (binaries)

and each one of them needs to have a different versions.

It might make sense to have tags like

- glycin-2.0.1

etc.

What is the problem you are having in practice and what's your suggestion to solve it?
This would help a lot for replacing the various load-at-size and load-at-scale apis that gdk-pixbuf has.
